AB  - This study addresses the challenges of fault diagnosis in the health status assessment of large-scale hydropower units by proposing a comprehensive methodology based on industrial big data analytics. The proposed approach encompasses data partitioning, data cleansing strategies, steady-state and non-steady-state health modeling, as well as degradation trend modeling. By performing large-scale mining of historical operational data, the algorithm can autonomously extract baseline features and safety boundaries of healthy operation under various working conditions, enabling differentiation between normal and abnormal states. Moreover, it facilitates early anomaly trend warning and degradation fault prediction. The methodology has been validated using real-world operational data from a large hydropower unit. The results demonstrate that the proposed method significantly improves the accuracy of health assessment models across diverse operating conditions, enables timely identification of abnormal signs, and achieves long-lead-time degradation warnings. The integration of fault diagnosis algorithms with industrial big data technologies notably enhances the intelligence and reliability of health status assessment for large-scale hydropower units, providing strong support for secure operation and maintenance decision-making.
ER  - 

