AB  - In the context of the ongoing electrification of energy usages and the integration of renewable energy capacity to address the challenges of climate change, several questions arise regarding the ability of the future electricity system to maintain the equilibrium between production and consumption, as new means for energy storage and transportation are developed. Historically in Europe, the task of balancing supply and demand for electricity has primarily fallen to thermal and hydro power plants, owing to their ability to swiftly adapt their power output on demand. However, as the average age of a hydropower plant in the continent is estimated to be 42 years, considering refurbishment dates, numerous challenges are foreseen concerning operational availability and security. Among various technologies considered, both proven and emerging, predictive maintenance holds particular significance for legacy powerplants.In this paper, we discuss the utilisation of autoencoder-type neural networks, based on the original proposition put forth by Hajimohammadali et al. to approximate the behaviours of hydro generator units during the operations, at varying levels of solicitation, environment conditions and phases of the production cycle. As such models were trained in data acquired on commercially exploited hydro generator units to produce a health indicator for trend degradation estimation, providing insight into the machine health status. It aims to tackle sector specific challenges for monitoring and maintenance of hydropower plants which are the distinctive designs, environment conditions and instrumentation levels between systems.
ER  - 

